  "A baker needs to make cookies and has 5 eggs and 3 cups of flour. Each batch requires 2 eggs and 1 cup of flour. What limits the number of batches, and how does this relate to limiting reagents?": "",
  "Eggs are limiting; 5 eggs make 2 full batches with 1 egg left over, like excess reagent remains": "",
  "Eggs are limiting; like a limiting reagent, they determine the maximum batches (2)": "",
  "Neither is limiting; both are used up exactly": "",
  "Flour is limiting; like a limiting reagent, it determines the maximum batches (3)": "",
  "With 5 eggs at 2 per batch, you can make only 2 full batches (using 4 eggs, with 1 egg excess). Flour allows 3 batches but is irrelevant since eggs run out first -- just like a limiting reagent in chemistry.": "",
  "A lab technician mixes 10.0 g of zinc with 15.0 g of hydrochloric acid according to: Zn + 2HCl -> ZnCl2 + H2. Which is the limiting reagent? (Molar masses: Zn = 65.4 g/mol, HCl = 36.5 g/mol)": "",
  "Zinc, because it has fewer grams": "",
  "Zinc, because it is completely consumed while HCl remains in excess": "",
  "Neither; both are consumed completely": "",
  "HCl, because there are not enough moles of HCl": "",
  "Moles of Zn = 10.0/65.4 = 0.153 mol; moles of HCl = 15.0/36.5 = 0.411 mol. Zn needs 2 x 0.153 = 0.306 mol HCl; we have 0.411 mol. Since there is more HCl than needed, Zn is limiting and is completely consumed first.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company reacts 50.0 g of salicylic acid (C7H6O3, MW = 138.1) with excess acetic anhydride to make aspirin (C9H8O4, MW = 180.2). What is the theoretical yield of aspirin?": "",
  "180.2 g": "",
  "50.0 g": "",
  "65.2 g": "",
  "138.1 g": "",
  "Moles of salicylic acid = 50.0/138.1 = 0.362 mol. The 1:1 ratio gives 0.362 mol aspirin. Mass = 0.362 x 180.2 = 65.2 g of aspirin.": "",
  "An engineer burns 100 g of methane (CH4, MW = 16) in a furnace with 200 g of O2 (MW = 32). According to CH4 + 2O2 -> CO2 + 2H2O, how many grams of CO2 are produced? (CO2 MW = 44)": "",
  "137.5 g": "",
  "300 g": "",
  "275 g": "",
  "200 g": "",
  "Moles: CH4 = 100/16 = 6.25 mol, O2 = 200/32 = 6.25 mol. CH4 requires 2 x 6.25 = 12.5 mol O2, but only 6.25 mol O2 is available, so O2 is limiting. 6.25 mol O2 / 2 = 3.125 mol CH4 consumed, producing 3.125 mol CO2 = 3.125 x 44 = 137.5 g.": "",
  "A student has 3.0 moles of Fe and 4.0 moles of O2 for the reaction 4Fe + 3O2 -> 2Fe2O3. What is the maximum number of moles of Fe2O3 that can be produced?": "",
  "3.0 moles": "",
  "2.67 moles": "",
  "1.5 moles": "",
  "2.0 moles": "",
  "Fe: 3.0 mol / 4 = 0.75 equivalents. O2: 4.0 mol / 3 = 1.33 equivalents. Fe has fewer equivalents, so Fe is limiting. 3.0 mol Fe x (2 mol Fe2O3 / 4 mol Fe) = 1.5 mol Fe2O3.": "",
  "A food scientist needs to produce carbon dioxide for carbonation. If 84 g of NaHCO3 (MW = 84) reacts with excess citric acid, how many liters of CO2 are produced at STP? (NaHCO3 decomposes to produce 1 mol CO2 per mol NaHCO3; molar volume at STP = 22.4 L)": "",
  "11.2 L": "",
  "22.4 L": "",
  "44.8 L": "",
  "33.6 L": "",
  "84 g NaHCO3 / 84 g/mol = 1 mol NaHCO3. This produces 1 mol CO2. At STP, 1 mol of gas = 22.4 L, so 22.4 L of CO2 is produced.": "",
  "A mining operation processes ore containing Fe2O3. If 500 g of Fe2O3 (MW = 159.7) is reduced with excess CO, how many grams of Fe can be obtained? (Fe2O3 + 3CO -> 2Fe + 3CO2; Fe MW = 55.85)": "",
  "349.6 g": "",
  "250 g": "",
  "175 g": "",
  "500 g": "",
  "Moles of Fe2O3 = 500/159.7 = 3.131 mol. From the equation, 1 mol Fe2O3 produces 2 mol Fe. So 3.131 x 2 = 6.262 mol Fe. Mass = 6.262 x 55.85 = 349.6 g Fe.": "",
  "A student reacts 20.0 g of NaOH (MW = 40) with 30.0 g of H2SO4 (MW = 98) in the reaction 2NaOH + H2SO4 -> Na2SO4 + 2H2O. How many grams of excess reagent remain?": "",
  "5.0 g NaOH": "",
  "5.49 g H2SO4": "",
  "5.5 g H2SO4": "",
  "10.0 g NaOH": "",
  "Moles NaOH = 20.0/40 = 0.500 mol; moles H2SO4 = 30.0/98 = 0.306 mol. NaOH needs 0.500/2 = 0.250 mol H2SO4. Since 0.306 > 0.250, NaOH is limiting. Excess H2SO4 = 0.306 - 0.250 = 0.056 mol = 0.056 x 98 = 5.49 g.": "",
  "An airbag inflates when sodium azide decomposes: 2NaN3 -> 2Na + 3N2. If an airbag requires 67.2 L of N2 at STP to inflate, how many grams of NaN3 are needed? (MW NaN3 = 65; molar volume at STP = 22.4 L)": "",
  "97.5 g": "",
  "130.0 g": "",
  "65.0 g": "",
  "195.0 g": "",
  "Moles N2 needed = 67.2/22.4 = 3.0 mol. From the equation, 3 mol N2 requires 2 mol NaN3. So 3.0 x (2/3) = 2.0 mol NaN3. Mass = 2.0 x 65 = 130.0 g.": "",
  "A water treatment plant uses chlorine gas to purify water. If 5.00 moles of Cl2 react with 5.00 moles of NaOH according to: Cl2 + 2NaOH -> NaCl + NaClO + H2O, how many moles of NaCl are produced and which reagent is in excess?": "",
  "2.50 mol NaCl; Cl2 is in excess": "",
  "5.00 mol NaCl; NaOH is in excess": "",
  "5.00 mol NaCl; neither is in excess": "",
  "2.50 mol NaCl; NaOH is in excess": "",
  "NaOH is limiting: 5.00 mol NaOH / 2 = 2.50 mol Cl2 needed. We have 5.00 mol Cl2, so Cl2 is in excess. 2.50 mol Cl2 reacts to produce 2.50 mol NaCl.": ""
